</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[96,1536,725,978]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
This group is widely distributed in eastern Australia with many colourful species, yet it was only recently discovered. 
<bibRefCitation author="Davies and Zabka" box="[272,623,757,791]" firstAuthor="Davies" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the Queensland Museum" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="189 - 266" part="27" refId="ref8537" refString="Davies, V. T. and M. Zabka. 1989. Illustrated keys to the genera of jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae) in Australia. Memoirs of the Queensland Museum 27: 189 - 266." title="Illustrated keys to the genera of jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae) in Australia" type="journal article" year="1989">Davies and Żabka (1989)</bibRefCitation>
figured a male 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baehr &amp; Whyte" authorityYear="2016" box="[846,951,761,791]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ottoi">
<emphasis box="[846,951,761,791]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. ottoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the vicinity of Brisbane, but did not give it a name. The most widely distributed species is 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Otto &amp; Hill" authorityYear="2013" box="[846,1012,798,828]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plumosus">
<emphasis box="[846,1012,798,828]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. plumosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, first found near Sydney. The male 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Otto &amp; Hill" authorityYear="2013" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plumosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. plumosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also the most atypical of the group, with feathery plumes that it extends to the rear above its elevated and partly expanded fan. Males of all other species in the group inflate their spinnerets as they display to females. All members of the group have an asymmetric display in which they alternately extend or kick one leg III to one side, then the other leg III to the other side.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
